metadata.name: Glossolalia #184
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It‚Äôs less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #106
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I‚Äôm always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There‚Äôs something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition

metadata.name: Primordial #186
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

metadata.name: Fields of the Abandoned Homeland #55
metadata.description:
This project was started in December 2021. At that time, I didn't know what the result would be. It was only an idea to create something memorable, you know, like a photo that people keep in their wallets, or a picture on someone's office desk, something that evokes warm and nostalgic emotions. I didn't have a specific plan, so I just focused on testing different mechanics that might be useful in my future drop. And then, in February 2022, the war came to my home. For two weeks, my family and I hid from bombs and rockets in the basement of our house, and finally, we were lucky enough to escape. We have been looking for a safe place to stay for months, and with several relocations, depression set in, and it was difficult to believe what was happening. I thought that such events only happened in movies and history textbooks. The only way to distract myself was by coding. And then, during one of our relocations, I realized what should be the main idea of this project. This is what I had watched for hours during every relocation. Whether it was a bus ride or a train ride, only the background changed, but the landscape was almost the same - endless Ukrainian wheat fields. Fields, some of which were occupied, burned, or simply turned into minefields. Fields symbolized by the yellow color on the flag of Ukraine. These are the fields I want to see again but in reverse order, on my way home. 

I dedicate this drop to everyone who, for whatever reason, had to leave their home against their will.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[4] to change resolution
- Press [s] to save

Made with p5js and hope
Copyright @Kitel87 || 2023

metadata.name: The Binding String #84
metadata.description:
........._____.........
......./+_+_+_+\.......
..|.../+/.._..\+\...\/.
..\|.|+|..|x|..|+|..|..
.\/___\+\.|_|./+/__/_|.

100% code. Typography hand-made by @nathansonic

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Press s to save.
Click the screen to pause the animation.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

This piece explores the interplay of our concepts of communication and the web.

The transaction hash creates the randomization but it‚Äôs also the protagonist in this story. It dons the stone and halo as the key for how the blockchain speaks to you.

The transaction hash is brought purposefully into the piece in order to recognize its significance almost as a deity in the generative process. It‚Äôs the one thin string binding our real-life experience with blockchain.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

If you want a larger scene with more detail (larger resolution), zoom out using the browser zoom. Be careful as the more you zoom out the more ground elements will be created to fill the scene.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Pricing - Dutch auction
The pricing is a Dutch auction set at 4 - 3 - 3. 433 is the number of randomized variables in the piece.

Mint amount
The mint amount is 170. 170 is the number of unique elements multiplied by 10.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string started with a focus on maximizing the possible variations.

This has led to the project having 433 randomizable variables that tweak the scene to create insane variation. A lot of this variation is very subtle, but it‚Äôs there.

Random variables: 433 = 281 (rand int) + 62 (rand float) + 90 (Perlin noise).

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

The binding string has multiple layered scene elements. Some of these elements interact. Plants are forced back by the halo, elements closer to the central glowing rock reflect more light etc. There are 17 elements in total.

Here are some of the elements that characterize the narrative and aesthetic:
Stone circle
Planets
Plants (trees, bushes)
Fireflies
Animated halo
Glyph text
A smart, fully randomized custom palette creator.
Geometric shapes
Atmosphere scenarios ( day, evening, night, foggy)
Rocks
Mossy-ness
Crystal Geodes
Skewed hills
Ground elements (mud, grass)
Math based lighting
Galaxy lines
Shadow dust

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

Extra special thanks to @nathansonic for his support, feedback, and code editions.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+

3rd party code used:
Various bits by @nathansonic, including a custom palette creator.
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+-+
